06470nam a22008415i 9781478022497DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20222022ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021030506  a97814780224977 a10.1515/97814780224972doi  a(DE-B1597)626005  a(OCoLC)1322124427  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC00aP96.F46 7aSOC0520002bisacsh00aRe-Understanding Media :bFeminist Extensions of Marshall McLuhan /ced. by Sarah Sharma, Rianka Singh. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface: The Centre on the Margins -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I Retrieving McLuhan’s Media -- t1 Transporting Blackness -- t2 Sidewalks of Concrete and Code -- t3 Hardwired -- t4 Textile, the Uneasy Medium -- tPart II Thinking with McLuhan: An Invitation -- t5 Dear Incubator -- t6 Wifesaver -- t7 “Will Miss File Misfile?” -- t8 Computers Made of Paper, Genders Made of Cards -- t9 Sky High -- tPart III Media after McLuhan -- t10 Scanning for Black Data -- t11 3D Printing and Digital Colonialism -- t12 Toward a Media Theory of the Digital Bundle -- tAfterword -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe contributors to Re-Understanding Media advance a feminist version of Marshall McLuhan’s key text, Understanding Media: The Extensions of Man, repurposing his insight that “the medium is the message” for feminist ends. They argue that while McLuhan’s theory provides a falsely universalizing conception of the technological as a structuring form of power, feminist critics can take it up to show how technologies alter and determine the social experiences of race, gender, class, and sexuality. This volume showcases essays, experimental writings, and interviews from media studies scholars, artists, activists, and those who work with and create technology. Among other topics, the contributors extend McLuhan’s discussion of transportation technology to the attics and cargo boxes that moved Black women through the Underground Railroad, apply McLuhan’s concept of media as extensions of humans to analyze Tupperware as media of containment, and take up 3D printing as a feminist and decolonial practice. The volume demonstrates how power dynamics are built into technological media and how media can be harnessed for radical purposes.Contributors. Nasma Ahmed, Morehshin Allahyari, Sarah Banet-Weiser, Wendy Hui Kyong Chun, Brooke Erin Duffy, Ganaele Langlois, Sara Martel, Shannon Mattern, Cait McKinney, Jeremy Packer, Craig Robertson, Sarah Sharma, Ladan Siad, Rianka Singh, Nicholas Taylor, Armond R. Towns, and Jennifer Wemigwans  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCommunication and technology. 0aFeminism and mass media. 0aMass mediaxSocial aspects. 0aTechnology and civilization. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh1 aBanet-Weiser, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuffy, Brooke Erin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKyong Chun, Wendy Hui, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLanglois, Ganaele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartel, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMattern, Shannon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKinney, Cait, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPacker, Jeremy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobertson, Craig, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb